      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To differentiate between administrative errors and actual theft, auditors typically use a combination of data analysis and investigative techniques. Here are some common methods:\n\n1. **Transaction analysis**: Reviewing transaction logs and invoices can help identify discrepancies between what was recorded and what was actually counted. This can help distinguish between errors and intentional theft.\n2. **Physical counts**: Conducting regular physical counts of inventory can provide an objective measure of the actual quantity on hand. This can help identify discrepancies between recorded and actual quantities.\n3. **Cycle counting**: This involves conducting regular counts of high-value or high-risk items to identify any discrepancies or anomalies.\n4. **Anomaly detection**: Using statistical analysis and machine learning algorithms can help identify unusual patterns or anomalies in inventory data that may indicate theft or other irregularities.\n5. **Interviews and observations**: Conducting interviews with employees and observing their behavior during counts can help identify any suspicious activity or inconsistencies in their stories.\n6. **Documentation review**: Reviewing documentation, such as receipts, invoices, and shipping records, can help identify any discrepancies or inconsistencies that may indicate theft or other irregularities.\n\nTo differentiate between administrative errors and actual theft, auditors may use the following criteria:\n\n* **Frequency and consistency**: If errors",
